@davisagli : There are two "lowest versions" in play. A previous version of the branch actually checked both but I ripped that out.

There's "probably does not even work right lowest" (which for us is Python 3.6, right now).

And there's "lowest that probably works but we want you to upgrade in the next X weeks" (which is 3.8 for us).

I ripped out the check for "probably does not even work right" because that one is checked by PIP and I couldn't trigger it because I couldn't get my Python environment itself into such a state.

I think that we only want the two "lowest" numbers to diverge for a few weeks every year or two, but they do diverge, as is the case right now.

@pconrad-sfdo : Similarly, the "best recommended version" is not usually the "lowest supported version", for several reasons like: higher versions may be more secure and performant. And also if we let users leapfrog then they are forced to upgrade less frequently. e.g. "we do support 3.8 but if you go right to 3.9 then you won't need to upgrade when we drop 3.8"

