Since we have to do run-time Contexts checks anyways, I've decided to specifically optimize for user convenience rather than strict type correctness. 

If we go for correctness, all functions would have to be generic to work correctly.
```typescript
// This is nice to write
async function allSolutions(api: Z3WithContext, solver: Solver): Promise<Model[]> {
  solver.push();
  const results = [];
  while ((await solver.check()) === sat) {
    const model = solver.model();
    results.push(model);
    solver.add(api.Or(...model.decls().map(decl => decl.neq(model.get(decl)))));
  }
  solver.pop();
  return results;
}

// This is harder
async function allSolutionsGeneric<ContextName extends string>(
  api: Z3WithContext<ContextName>,
  solver: Solver<ContextName>,
): Promise<Model<ContextName>[]> {
  // ...
}
```

It gets even more unwieldy with complicated types
```typescript
function createMapping(api: Z3WithContext, bools: BoolRef[], ints: ArithRef[]): AstMap<BoolRef, ArithRef> {
  const map = new api.AstMap<BoolRef, ArithRef>();
  for (const [bool, int] of zip(bools, ints)) {
    map.set(bool, int);
  }
  return map;
}

function createMappingGeneric<ContextName extends string>(
  api: Z3WithContext<ContextName>,
  bools: BoolRef<ContextName>[],
  ints: ArithRef<ContextName>[],
): AstMap<BoolRef<ContextName>, ArithRef<ContextName>, ContextName> {
  const map = new api.AstMap<BoolRef<ContextName>, ArithRef<ContextName>>();
  for (const [bool, int] of zip(bools, ints)) {
    map.set(bool, int);
  }
  return map;
}
```

Having a default name for context will not alleviate the problem either.
```typescript
export interface Solver<Name extends string = 'main'> {
  /* ... */
}

declare function allSolutions(api: Z3WithContext, solver: Solver): Promise<Model[]>;

// This will now fail to compile, you have to make all of your functions generic anyways
allSolutions(new createContext('myContext').Solver())
```

Also should we have a default name, the same omission problem you've noticed could occur as well.

@ericl The tricky part is that the owner might not call the actor after it created the actor (or at least within a certain period), while other callers which actually call the actor can learn the actor failure, they are not authorized to publish the actor death event to gcs. Thus it seems not feasible to rely on ray call from the owner to detect it.

Also some of the scenarios actually requires very prompt actor failure detection (they require the actor being reconstructed within a second).

For now I plan to move the publishing of actor event to raylet in this PR. We can revisit this later and see how this is bestly done. What do you think?

@davisagli - I think my comment can be improved here. In this case the `ConnectionError` is coming from the `responses` module. In this case, we add a response that contains the `head=` url parameter. The first time we call `get_pull_request_by_branch_name` the given branch name matches the expected parameter value.

In the next case we use a value for `head` that doesn't exist and so the endpoint doesn't fully match the response that we added so it fails with a `ConnectionError`. 

[The docs](https://github.com/getsentry/responses) state, 'If you attempt to fetch a url which doesn't hit a match, responses will raise a ConnectionError'

@jsirois @stuhood @benjyw @blorente  any opposition that this uses `--timeout-disabled` rather than `--timeouts`? 

The main motivation was to use the same naming scheme as `--timeout-default` and `--timeout-maximum`.

Then, our thinking was that the main use case for this option is when people want to turn off timeouts when iterating on code, so it's more natural to write `--timeout-disabled` than `--no-timeout-enabled`.

